POC 1
The Requirements Agent — BDD Specialist
Goal
Turn vague natural-language feature requests into 
structured, unambiguous Gherkin scenarios (.feature 
files).
Pattern
Critic / Refinement Loop
How It Works
• Agent 1 — Author: Drafts initial user stories and 
acceptance criteria from the raw requirement.
• Agent 2 — Verifier/Critic: Acts as QA Lead, flagging 
ambiguity, missing edge cases, and untestable 
statements.
• Feedback loops back until a quality threshold is met, 
then the clean .feature file is written to the 
workspace.
POC 2
The Design Agent — Schema & Contract Architect
Goal
Read generated .feature files and automatically produce a technical 
design spec — database schemas and API contracts.
Pattern
Tool-Use (Routing)
Hands-On Learning Point
Your team learns to give an LLM a defined set of Python functions —
read_file(), write_file() — that let it operate directly inside the 
local directory.
POC 3
The Coding & Testing Agent — Test-Driven Generator
Goal
Write application code and unit tests, then self-correct until all tests pass.
Pattern
Human-in-the-Loop + Execution Sandbox
The Core Loop
01
Read api_spec.json and db_schema.sql, generate FastAPI boilerplate.
02
Generate pytest file from BDD scenarios.
03
Execute pytest via run_command tool in the local terminal.
04
Read traceback, patch source code, re-run — repeat until 100% pass rate.
IMPLEMENTATION GUIDE
Self-Correcting Coding Agent: Write → Test → Fix Loop
A minimal, end-to-end implementation of an autonomous code-fix agent using Python, FastAPI, and the OpenAI / Azure OpenAI library. The agent runs a tight Write → Test → 
Fix loop, exposing two tools to the LLM: one to overwrite application code, and one to run pytest and return terminal output.
Write Code
Apply Fixes
Run Tests
Collect Failures
Each cycle appends fresh error traces to the message history, driving iterative correction until tests pass or the iteration cap is reached.
Prerequisites
•
Install openai and pytest in your workspace
•
•
Prepare a target file to fix — e.g. a broken calc.py
Write a corresponding test_calc.py test suite
The Agent Loop (agent.py)
This script orchestrates the full cycle: it executes tests, evaluates output, and feeds 
failure logs back to the LLM. The loop terminates when all tests pass or the 
maximum iteration count is reached.
TEAM LEARNING OUTCOMES
What Your Team Learns by Building This From 
Scratch
When your team implements this sequence themselves, they encounter foundational agentic-system concepts that are difficult to grasp from 
documentation alone.
The Tool Abstraction
The model does not execute Python or 
access the terminal. It outputs a 
structured JSON payload requesting an 
action. The local script acts as the 
"operating system" — interpreting and 
executing each command. This 
separation of intent and execution is 
the cornerstone of safe agentic design.
State Control Friction
If the model edits code but forgets to 
call run_tests(), the loop stalls. 
Teams learn how prompt engineering 
and stricter system control loops 
enforce behavioural pacing — ensuring 
the agent always signals the next step.
Context Window Expansion
Each execution cycle appends new 
error traces to the messages array, 
making token consumption visible in 
real time. Teams observe how 
conversational memory grows across 
extended debugging runs — and why 
truncation strategies and summary 
compression become essential at scale.
